#: ../../catalogs.rst:56
# f2b34b428dc34c9f9254e1d0a9794798
msgid "Prefixes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:62
# 93ea51ad54b347ae916a1fdaff6e39c0
msgid "Prefix rules allow you to add a prefix to book listings when certain criteria are met. For example, you might want to mark books you've read with a checkmark, or books on your wishlist with an X."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:64
# 6224d96a5b814a40bbc0e1889e5ae627
msgid "The checkbox in the first column enables the rule. :guilabel:`Name` is a rule name that you provide. :guilabel:`Field` is either :guilabel:`Tags` or a custom column from your library. :guilabel:`Value` is the content of :guilabel:`Field` to match. When a prefix rule is satisfied, the book will be marked with the selected :guilabel:`Prefix`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:66
# 4812c50fb0a84e7db286eb6dcf706582
msgid "Three prefix rules have been specified in the example above:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:68
# 841934ca5bf54759aa4bbf372efd85be
msgid ":guilabel:`Read book` specifies that a book with any date in a custom column named :guilabel:`Last read` will be prefixed with a checkmark symbol."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:69
# 96f4b48b26d04c588cc1f2cd11fda40e
msgid ":guilabel:`Wishlist` item specifies that any book with a :guilabel:`Wishlist` tag will be prefixed with an X symbol."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:70
# 9eedcc379af642bdb0988804fd422cdd
msgid ":guilabel:`Library` books specifies that any book with a value of True (or Yes) in a custom column :guilabel:`Available in Library` will be prefixed with a double arrow symbol."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:72
# f0c29fc36e2e418b9d7ae2f9c6bc5973
msgid "The first matching rule supplies the prefix. Disabled or incomplete rules are ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:75
# 5eb841831027424aafb4b93231dd6236
msgid "Excluded books"
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:81
# fe063b4e47c14257810d9b57d9ac54a5
msgid "Exclusion rules allow you to specify books that will not be cataloged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:83
# f4c33bdf6474401cb58a14ed47313415
msgid "The checkbox in the first column enables the rule. :guilabel:`Name` is a rule name that you provide. :guilabel:`Field` is either :guilabel:`Tags` or a custom column in your library. :guilabel:`Value` is the content of :guilabel:`Field` to match. When an exclusion rule is satisfied, the book will be excluded from the generated catalog."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:85
# bc4cfeda1533400ebde6590845730e9d
msgid "Two exclusion rules have been specified in the example above:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:87
# 443f411f1e964c4d80879e5f54b2b36a
msgid "The :guilabel:`Catalogs` rule specifies that any book with a :guilabel:`Catalog` tag will be excluded from the generated catalog."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:88
# 3218add7f5474523bb20174db711ccda
msgid "The :guilabel:`Archived` Books rule specifies that any book with a value of :guilabel:`Archived` in the custom column :guilabel:`Status` will be excluded from the generated catalog."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:90
# e18cb33b725f461596632b049e39ce49
msgid "All rules are evaluated for every book. Disabled or incomplete rules are ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:95
# 2e2e4b1842534a23bb5b25a82791cd48
msgid "Excluded genres"
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:101
# fecae24eacd34c918cef7362eef3f2ad
msgid "When the catalog is generated, tags in your database are used as genres. For example, you may use the tags ``Fiction`` and ``Nonfiction``. These tags become genres in the generated catalog, with books listed under their respective genre lists based on their assigned tags. A book will be listed in every genre section for which it has a corresponding tag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:103
# 532d9373700c4ec981c650849932bbf1
msgid "You may be using certain tags for other purposes, perhaps a + to indicate a read book, or a bracketed tag like ``[Amazon Freebie]`` to indicate a book's source. The :guilabel:`Excluded genres` regex allows you to specify tags that you don't want used as genres in the generated catalog. The default exclusion regex pattern ``\\[.+\\]\\+`` excludes any tags of the form ``[tag]``, as well as excluding ``+``, the default tag for read books, from being used as genres in the generated catalog."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:105
# beb57efba9c5485ca1f9b3114b75cbbb
msgid "You can also use an exact tag name in a regex. For example, ``[Amazon Freebie]`` or ``[Project Gutenberg]``. If you want to list multiple exact tags for exclusion, put a pipe (vertical bar) character between them: ``[Amazon Freebie]|[Project Gutenberg]``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:107
# c4a3349c973e4b01a0f4ebdd32ceb86e
msgid ":guilabel:`Results of regex` shows you which tags will be excluded when the catalog is built, based on the tags in your database and the regex pattern you enter. The results are updated as you modify the regex pattern."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:110
# ae122e8d8d634391895a6371b5f939ba
msgid "Other options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:116
# fb407e9474bf4f3f925b18ee7dbc2421
msgid ":guilabel:`Catalog cover` specifies whether to generate a new cover or use an existing cover. It is possible to create a custom cover for your catalogs - see :ref:`Custom catalog covers` for more information. If you have created a custom cover that you want to reuse, select :guilabel:`Use existing cover`. Otherwise, select :guilabel:`Generate new cover`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:118
# 80e857895b804073bd8ca2ac2cce68c8
msgid ":guilabel:`Extra Description note` specifies a custom column's contents to be inserted into the Description page, next to the cover thumbnail. For example, you might want to display the date you last read a book using a :guilabel:`Last Read` custom column. For advanced use of the Description note feature, see `this post in the calibre forum <http://www.mobileread.com/forums/showpost.php?p=1335767&postcount=395>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:120
# b5322d603f924fff854289c8e64557e3
msgid ":guilabel:`Thumb width` specifies a width preference for cover thumbnails included with Descriptions pages. Thumbnails are cached to improve performance.To experiment with different widths, try generating a catalog with just a few books until you've determined your preferred width, then generate your full catalog. The first time a catalog is generated with a new thumbnail width, performance will be slower, but subsequent builds of the catalog will take advantage of the thumbnail cache."
msgstr ""

#: ../../catalogs.rst:122
# cd846e7b160642609f96e67b45af3ac0
msgid ":guilabel:`Merge with Comments` specifies a custom column whose content will be non-destructively merged with the Comments metadata during catalog generation. For example, you might have a custom column :guilabel:`Author Bio` that you'd like to append to the Comments metadata. You can choose to insert the custom column contents *before or after* the Comments section, and optionally separate the appended content with a horizontal rule separator. Eligible custom column types include ``text, comments, and composite``."
msgstr ""

